# flatland_forward.tas — fly straight ahead on flatland and watch chunks generate.
#
# Purpose: expose the per-frame spikes caused by chunk mesh generation as the
# player crosses chunk boundaries on an otherwise empty flat world. Used by
# examples/voxel/docs/chunk-size-investigation.md — see that file for the
# baseline numbers and the 16- / 32- / 48-wide chunk comparison.
#
# What it does:
#   1. t=1..2    Click left mouse to capture the mouse (gameplay input gates on this).
#   2. t=3       Double-tap Space (press 1 of 2) — first tap of the fly-mode toggle.
#   3. t=5       Double-tap Space (press 2 of 2) — within DOUBLE_TAP_WINDOW = 0.3 s
#                (36 ticks at 120 Hz), flips player.fly_mode = true. Flying means
#                no gravity, no ground clipping — purely a constant-velocity
#                probe of the chunk-generation pipeline.
#   4. t=7       keydown W — start flying straight ahead (-Z at spawn yaw).
#   5. t=1207    keyup W — stop after 1200 sim ticks ≈ 10 wall seconds at 120 Hz
#                sim rate. FLY_SPEED = 10 blocks/s → 100 blocks forward →
#                ~2.1 chunks crossed at CHUNK_W=48, ~6.3 at CHUNK_W=16.
#                That is enough to force the mesh radius to walk past the
#                spawn ring and trigger chunk generation + meshing on the hot
#                path.
#   6. t=1400    Hold steady so the last few async mesh-gen passes can
#                drain and the frame dump captures a stable view.
#
# Sean's exact ask (voxel/chunk-size-perf branch): "make a tas run spawn in a
# flatlands world and fly forwards until chunks generate. it's really slow! I
# want you to see it be slow." The profile CSV captured under
# `--profile-csv=<path>` is the "see it be slow" output.
#
# Usage (from utils/swindowzig):
#   zig build native -Dexample=voxel
#   ./zig-out/bin/voxel --headless --world=flatland \
#     --tas examples/voxel/tests/flatland_forward.tas \
#     --dump-frame=/tmp/flatland_forward.ppm \
#     --profile-csv=/tmp/flatland_before.csv
#
# Tick numbering is relative to the first post-loading tick (the replayer is
# gated during world load by the TAS remap in main.zig), so tick 1 is always
# the first frame of actual gameplay, regardless of how long pregen took.

# --- Capture mouse (gameplay input gates on mouse_captured) ---
1 mouse_down left
2 mouse_up left

# --- Double-tap Space to enter fly mode ---
3 keydown Space
4 keyup Space
5 keydown Space
6 keyup Space

# --- Fly forward for 1200 ticks (-Z at default spawn yaw) ---
7 keydown W
1207 keyup W

# --- Hold steady so async mesh work drains before the frame capture ---
1400 mouse_move 0 0
